{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5a782bf7-aa73-4b96-9e1f-562c9b2506f7","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it to speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If you can't install tools in the container, use the **sidecar approach** — add an ephemeral or debug container with the SDK, then attach via `dotnet-trace` using the shared process namespace (`shareProcessNamespace: true` in your pod spec). Alternatively, if `dotnet-monitor` is already deployed as a sidecar, you can hit its `/trace` HTTP endpoint directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"503cfea9-1af7-49e9-8db2-d158ce8c1357","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":415},"id":"4027a19c-79c8-4d04-b907-2e35fef4bdf8","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:47:33.544Z","parentId":"83d1de41-0eb5-4686-b711-738baac22654"}
